@startuml fig-http11-vs-http2
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title HTTP/1.1 vs HTTP/2 — Multiplexing

participant "Client" as C #FFE0B2
participant "Server" as S #C8E6C9

== HTTP/1.1 — Sequential (Head-of-Line Blocking) ==

C -> S : GET /index.html
S --> C : 200 index.html
C -> S : GET /style.css
S --> C : 200 style.css
C -> S : GET /app.js
S --> C : 200 app.js

note right of S
  Each request must wait
  for the previous response.
end note

== HTTP/2 — Multiplexed Streams ==

C -[#1565C0]> S : Stream 1: GET /index.html
C -[#1565C0]> S : Stream 3: GET /style.css
C -[#1565C0]> S : Stream 5: GET /app.js

S -[#43A047]-> C : Stream 5: app.js (first to complete)
S -[#43A047]-> C : Stream 3: style.css
S -[#43A047]-> C : Stream 1: index.html

note right of S
  Responses arrive in any order.
  No head-of-line blocking.
end note

legend right
  HTTP/1.1 serialises requests on one connection.
  HTTP/2 multiplexes independent streams over
  a single TCP connection with header compression.
  Semantics (methods, status codes) remain identical.
endlegend
@enduml
